INSERT INTO `stations` VALUES (1,1,'Olkaria Geothermal Power Stations','<p><strong>Location </strong></p>\r\n<p>Olkaria Geothermal Project is situated within Hell&rsquo;s Gate National Park 120KM from Nairobi and neighbours horticultural farms that produce some of the finest flowers in the world. The project is also adjacent to Lake Naivasha, which is a fresh water lake in the Kenya Rift and a Ramsar site.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Geothermal Phenomenon</strong></p>\r\n<p>Geothermal energy is the natural heat stored within the earth&rsquo;s crust. The energy is manifested on the earth&rsquo;s surface in the form of fumaroles, hot springs and hot-altered grounds. To extract this energy, wells are drilled to tap steam and water at high temperatures (250-350oC) and pressures (600-1200 PSI) at depths of 1-3KM. For electricity generation, the steam is piped to a turbine, which rotates a generator to produce electrical energy.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Geothermal Development in Kenya</strong></p>\r\n<p>Exploration for geothermal resources in Kenya started in 1950&rsquo;s and gained momentum in the 1960&rsquo;s, when two wells were drilled at Olkaria. From 1967, the United Nations Development Programme (UNDP) in collaboration with the Kenya Government and the then East African Power and Lighting Company Ltd., conducted geological and geophysical surveys in the area between Lake Bogoria and Olkaria. The studies identified Olkaria as the most prospective area leading to the construction of the first geothermal power station between 1981 and 1984.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Power for the Future</strong></p>\r\n<p>Since geothermal energy is indigenous, renewable and environmentally benign, and is not prone to adverse weather, KenGen and the Ministry of Energy have fast tracked the expansion of electricity generation from geothermal resources. Preliminary studies indicate that a large potential of geothermal energy approximately 10,000MW exists within the Kenya Rift.</p>\r\n<p>The high potential areas that are yet to be fully explored include Suswa, Longonot, Eburru, Menengai, Silali, Emurauangogolak, Paka, Korosi and Barrier volcanoes.&nbsp; It is estimated that more than 4,000MW of electricity can be generated from these prospects. Under its G2G strategy, KenGen plans to increase to 782.2MW from geothermal resource by the year 2021.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Olkaria Geothermal System</strong></p>\r\n<p>The heat source of the geothermal system at Olkaria is due to intrusion of hot magma bodies to depths of less than 6 KM from the surface.&nbsp; Parts of the magma extruded to the surface to form the numerous hills and dome that dot the Olkaria landscape. The Ololbutot lava erupted about 200 years ago attesting to the youthfulness of the volcanic activity at Olkaria.</p>\r\n<p>The geothermal system at Olkaria consists of a two-phase reservoir that is hosted within 0.9-1.65 million-year old fractured trachyte and rhyolite rocks at depths of between 600M and 3000M. At the Olkaria East, Olkaria Domes field and Olkaria North East Geothermal fields, wells with a nominal diameter of 8 inches are drilled into the reservoir and the upper 700M-1200M cased off to avoid cold fluid inflow into the bore. The wells produce 75% water and 25% steam.&nbsp; Separation of steam is done using cyclone separators from where dry steam is piped to the powerhouse and separated water injected back into the reservoir.</p>\r\n<p><strong>KenGen&rsquo;s Geothermal Power Plants</strong></p>\r\n<p>KenGen owns four geothermal power stations, Olkaria I, Olkaria II, Olkaria IV and Olkaria I unit 4 &amp; 5.&nbsp; In addition to the Power stations, KenGen own fifteen wellheads generation plants one at Eburru and fourteen at Olkaria.</p>\r\n<p>The Geothermal Power Plants have a combined generation capacity of 533.5MW.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Olkaria I Power Station</strong></p>\r\n<p>Olkaria I Power Station was the first geothermal power plant in Africa. The 45 MW plant was commissioned in three phases and has three units each generating 15MW of electricity. The first unit was commissioned in June 1981, the second and third units in November 1982 and March 1985, respectively.</p>\r\n<p>A total of 33 wells were drilled for the station. Thirty-one of these are currently connected to the power station while two of these are retired. One of which is currently being used for hot re-injection. The turbines are direct condensing 4-stage running with an inlet steam pressure of 5 bars at temperatures of 152oC and steam consumption of 9.2 t/h/MW. The plant has had an average availability factor of over 95 per cent from commissioning. The power generated is connected to the national grid via a 132KV-transmission line.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Olkaria II Power Station</strong></p>\r\n<p>Located in the North Eastern sector of the greater Olkaria Geothermal field and commissioned in 2003, Olkaria II Power Station generates 105 MW. Initially, the power plant generated 70 MW from two units of 35 MW each. Later a third 35 MW unit was added. Construction of the third unit commenced in 2009 and was completed in May 2010, bringing the total generation capacity to 105 MW.</p>\r\n<p>Wells were drilled between 1986 and 1993 but construction of the power plant was delayed until the year 2000 when funds became available. The project was co-financed by the World Bank, the European Investment Bank, KfW of Germany and KenGen. Designed and constructed with an advantage of newer technology, this state- of- the- art plant is highly efficient in steam utilization.&nbsp; It works on single flash plant cycle with a steam consumption of 7.5 t/h/MW. The turbines are single flow six stage condensing with direct contact spray jet condenser. The power generated is transmitted to the national grid via 220 KV double circuit line.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Olkaria I Unit 4 &amp; 5 and Olkaria IV Power Station</strong></p>\r\n<p>Olkaria IV and Olkaria I unit 4 &amp; 5 each generating 140 MW were commissioned in December 2014 and February 2015 respectively. This is the country&rsquo;s largest Geothermal Power Project. Olkaria I unit 4 &amp; 5 is located at Olkaria East of the Olkaria geothermal field whereas Olkaria IV is at the Olkaria domes field.</p>\r\n<p>The projects were funded by KenGen and bilateral partners such as World Bank, Japan International Cooperation Agency (JICA), European Investment Agency (EIB), Africa Development Bank and KfW.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Eburru Wellhead Generation Plant</strong></p>\r\n<p>The Company engaged a consultant and contractor for the construction of the Eburru Wellhead plant that has a generation capability of 2.5 MW. The plant will be upgraded to 25 MW. The Eburru geothermal field is estimated to have a potential of more than 50MW. Use of the wellhead technology enables early generation of electricity from single wells before construction of large power plants. This early generation will avail more power to the country.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Olkaria Wellhead Generation Plants </strong></p>\r\n<p>The Company has installed fourteen wellhead generating units with a capacity of 81MW in the Olkaria Geothermal field. A pilot wellhead generating unit was commissioned in February 2012. The unit is installed at well OW-37A, which is located within the Olkaria East geothermal field.</p>\r\n<p>Direct Uses of Geothermal Energy</p>\r\n<p>Direct uses of geothermal energy in Kenya are fast gaining momentum with development of green houses and recreational facilities among other uses. The uses of geothermal energy for heating of green houses and enrich carbon dioxide levels for plant growth was championed by Oserian Development Company in their flower farms. Other uses include pyrethrum drying, potted water from condensed steam and fish farming.</p>\r\n<p><strong>On-going Projects</strong></p>\r\n<p><strong>Olkaria V, (158MW) and Olkaria I Unit 6 (83.3MW) projects</strong></p>\r\n<p>Construction of 158MW plant at Olkaria V in the North Eastern sector of the field is at the advanced stage, commissioning of the plant is set to be done in July 2019 . There is enough steam for the ongoing Olkaria V and Olkaria I Unit 6 projects. Steam for the modular plants has also been realized as well as for the Public Private Partnership Project Olkaria VI. The team is currently drilling for Olkaria VII.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Industrial Parks</strong></p>\r\n<p>Kenya Electricity Generating Company (KenGen) has set aside 1,300 acres in Olkaria for the construction of Industrial Parks. Five sites have already been identified for the park within Olkaria targeting high consumers of electricity.</p>','<p>Lorem Ipsum is simply dummy text of the printing and typesetting industry. Lorem Ipsum has been the industry\'s standard dummy text ever since the 1500s, when an unknown printer took a galley of type and scrambled it to make a type specimen book. <br>It has survived not only five centuries, but also the leap into electronic typesetting, remaining essentially unchanged. It was popularised in the 1960s with the release of Letraset sheets containing Lorem Ipsum passages, and more recently with desktop publishing software like Aldus PageMaker including versions of Lorem Ipsum</p>','',0,80,1,365,4,'olkaria.jpg','https://www.google.com/maps/embed?pb=!1m18!1m12!1m3!1d31914.790312929385!2d36.2866399752519!3d-0.8790175981393392!2m3!1f0!2f0!3f0!3m2!1i1024!2i768!4f13.1!3m3!1m2!1s0x182936f7bd090ad5%3A0x35ba1897fd346997!2sOlkaria%20I%20Power%20Plant%2C%20Nakuru!5e0!3m2!1sen!2ske!4v1581578762719!5m2!1sen!2ske','Address: P. O. BOX 785, 20117 Naivasha\r\nTel: 0711036000\r\nContact Person:Geothermal Development Director','12',1,1,'2019-09-23 10:00:00'),(2,4,'Kiambere Hydro Power Station','<p><strong>Installed Capacity</strong>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;2 x 84MW</p>\r\n<p><strong>Year of commissioning</strong> &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp; 1988&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>Turbine manufacturer</strong>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; MIL/Voith</p>\r\n<p><strong>Generator manufacturer</strong>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; MIL/Voith</p>\r\n<p><strong>Estimated cost&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </strong>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; Kshs. 4 billion (1988)</p>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\">The station, situated 220 km North East of Nairobi was commissioned in 1988 with two vertical generating units rated 72MW each. The machines were upgraded to 84 MW each in 2008/9. It has a 585 million cubic meter reservoir equipped with a free overflow spillway, a low level outlet at the main dam, an emergency spillway and intake at the saddle dam. The emergency spillway is provided for to mitigate against extreme floods. The underground power house is situated 4 kilometers away from the saddle dam where the intake structure is situated. The water conveyance to the machines is by a 6 meter diameter headrace tunnel.</div>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\">&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\"><sup>&nbsp;</sup></div>','<ol>\r\n<li>Do not litter the compound. Segregate waste and put in the designated waste bins. green bins are for biodegradables and red bins are for non-biodegradable waste.</li>\r\n<li>Visitors are advised not to wear high heeled and open shoes.</li>\r\n<li>Do not lean on the guard rails.</li>\r\n<li>Do not run down the stairs.</li>\r\n<li>Do not touch panels, wires, switch buttons or any equipment.</li>\r\n<li>In case of any fire alarm, do not panic. follow the guide&rsquo;s instructions. he will lead you to emergency assembly point.</li>\r\n<li>Smoking is strictly prohibited in the stations except in the designated smoking zones.</li>\r\n<li>Carrying and use of drugs and alcohol is strictly prohibited.</li>\r\n<li>Provide a list of names of members of your team to the guide and sign the provided form after the EHS awareness briefing.</li>\r\n<li>Photography is prohibited. Visitors will not be allowed tio use data storage devices, for example: flash drives or hard drives. Such devices must be deposited with the security guard at the entrance gate.</li>\r\n<li>Unless authorized, do not connect to the KenGen plants\' communication network(Wi-Fi).</li>\r\n</ol>','',0,160,1,365,4,'kiambere.jpg','https://www.google.com/maps/embed?pb=!1m18!1m12!1m3!1d15812.387104763447!2d81.42267604318599!3d7.779562931858755!2m3!1f0!2f0!3f0!3m2!1i1024!2i768!4f13.1!3m3!1m2!1s0x3afb2bffffffffff%3A0xaae54d72ca1b3cff!2sThe%20Kiambere%20Hydroelectric%20Power%20Station!5e0!3m2!1sen!2ske!4v1581576875612!5m2!1sen!2ske','<p>P. O. BOX 205, 60100, Embu</p>\r\n<p>Tel: 0711036351/0711035810</p>','7',2,1,'2019-09-23 10:00:00'),(3,4,'Masinga Hydro Power Station ','<p><strong>Installed Capacity </strong>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; 2 x 20 MW</p>\r\n<p><strong>Year of commissioning </strong>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp; 1981</p>\r\n<p><strong>Turbine manufacturer&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</strong>&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; ESCHER WYSS/Andritz</p>\r\n<p><strong>Generator manufacturer</strong> &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; (ABB) ASEA BROWN BOVERI/Andritz</p>\r\n<p><strong>Estimated cost of Development </strong>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; Kshs. 1.5 Billion &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\">Masinga is the main reservoir in the cascade, with a capacityof 1.56 billion cubic meters of water and is therefore used for water regulation throughout the year. The dam has an emergency spillway to mitigate excessive flooding and ogee weir free overflow spillway. The water is conveyed to the machines via two 3.5 meter wide penstock, one for each machine. The dam is equipped with a low level outlet gated channel which is used to maintain the cascade when the dam level falls below the minimun operating level of 1035 meters above sea level.&nbsp; The vertical Kaplan turbines drive two generators capable of generating 40MW of power. The power generated at Masinga is transmitted to Kamburu and Mt. Kenya region. From Kamburu, power is transmitted to Nairobi through two 220kv lines. The resovior occupies a surface area of 120Km2.&nbsp;</div>','<ol>\r\n<li>Do not litter the compound. Segregate waste and put in the designated waste bins. green bins are for biodegradables and red bins are for non-biodegradable waste.</li>\r\n<li>Visitors are advised not to wear high heeled and open shoes.</li>\r\n<li>Do not lean on the guard rails.</li>\r\n<li>Do not run down the stairs.</li>\r\n<li>Do not touch panels, wires, switch buttons or any equipment.</li>\r\n<li>In case of any fire alarm, do not panic. follow the guide&rsquo;s instructions. he will lead you to emergency assembly point.</li>\r\n<li>Smoking is strictly prohibited in the stations except in the designated smoking zones.</li>\r\n<li>Carrying and use of drugs and alcohol is strictly prohibited.</li>\r\n<li>Provide a list of names of members of your team to the guide and sign the provided form after the EHS awareness briefing.</li>\r\n<li>Photography is prohibited. Visitors will not be allowed tio use data storage devices, for example: flash drives or hard drives. Such devices must be deposited with the security guard at the entrance gate.</li>\r\n<li>Unless authorized, do not connect to the KenGen plants\' communication network(Wi-Fi).</li>\r\n</ol>','',0,160,90,365,4,'masinga.jpg','https://www.google.com/maps/embed?pb=!1m18!1m12!1m3!1d63829.39952290342!2d37.55940757910155!3d-0.8895498999999994!2m3!1f0!2f0!3f0!3m2!1i1024!2i768!4f13.1!3m3!1m2!1s0x18260c6243614b19%3A0xe3e0a9e5989eb252!2sMasinga%20Hydroelectric%20Power%20Station!5e0!3m2!1sen!2ske!4v1581577393037!5m2!1sen!2ske','Address:P. O. BOX 205, 60100 Embu\r\nTel: 0711036000\r\nContact Person:Regional Manager,Eastern','10',3,1,'2019-09-23 10:00:00'),(4,4,'Kamburu Hydro Power Station ','<p><strong>Installed Capacity</strong>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;3 x 31.4 MW</p>\r\n<p><strong>Year of commissioning</strong>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;1974</p>\r\n<p><strong>Turbine manufacturer</strong>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;LITOSTROJ</p>\r\n<p><strong>Generator manufacturer</strong>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;RADE KONCAR</p>\r\n<p><strong>Estimated cost of Development</strong>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;Kshs. 325 Million &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\">This was the first underground power station in the Seven Forks cascade, it was constructed in the early seventies by Yugoslav Companies and European construction consortiums.<br /><br /></div>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\">The Francis Runner Turbine utilises water from the Thiba and Tana rivers and generate power at 11kV through 3 air-cooled generators. All the governors and excitation systems of the machines have recently been replaced with new ones. Electric power from Kamburu is conveyed to Nairobi via two 220kV-transmission lines from a primary 132kV substation. The water is conveyed from the dam to the machines via one headrace tunneland branches&nbsp; at the powerhouse to supply the 3 machines. Kamburu hydraulic radial spillway gates (3 nos) are&nbsp; capable of discharging 4,500 cubic meters of water. Water is conveyed to the next power station (Gitaru) via a 2.9 Kilometer tailrace tunnel.</div>','<ol>\r\n<li>Do not litter the compound. Segregate waste and put in the designated waste bins. green bins are for biodegradables and red bins are for non-biodegradable waste.</li>\r\n<li>Visitors are advised not to wear high heeled and open shoes.</li>\r\n<li>Do not lean on the guard rails.</li>\r\n<li>Do not run down the stairs.</li>\r\n<li>Do not touch panels, wires, switch buttons or any equipment.</li>\r\n<li>In case of any fire alarm, do not panic. follow the guide&rsquo;s instructions. he will lead you to emergency assembly point.</li>\r\n<li>Smoking is strictly prohibited in the stations except in the designated smoking zones.</li>\r\n<li>Carrying and use of drugs and alcohol is strictly prohibited.</li>\r\n<li>Provide a list of names of members of your team to the guide and sign the provided form after the EHS awareness briefing.</li>\r\n<li>Photography is prohibited. Visitors will not be allowed tio use data storage devices, for example: flash drives or hard drives. Such devices must be deposited with the security guard at the entrance gate.</li>\r\n<li>Unless authorized, do not connect to the KenGen plants\' communication network(Wi-Fi).</li>\r\n</ol>','<ul>\r\n<li>Matendeni camp</li>\r\n<li>Kivaa KenGen Sand Dam</li>\r\n</ul>',0,160,1,365,4,'kamburu.jpg','https://www.google.com/maps/embed?pb=!1m18!1m12!1m3!1d3989.423142724771!2d37.68393071409875!3d-0.8064191355168004!2m3!1f0!2f0!3f0!3m2!1i1024!2i768!4f13.1!3m3!1m2!1s0x18266c5498e1c999%3A0xfa40b6feabe0a7b3!2sKamburu%20Hydroelectrical%20Power%20Plant!5e0!3m2!1sen!2ske!4v1581576689729!5m2!1sen!2ske','Address:P. O. BOX 205, 60100 Embu\r\nTel: 0711036000\r\nContact Person: Regional Manager,Eastern','8',5,1,'2019-09-23 10:00:00'),(5,5,'Wanjii Hydro Power Station ','<p>Wanjii power station is situated in Murang&rsquo;aCounty &nbsp;80km from Nairobi. This is a run-of-river plant with a small sized dam having low water storage capacity. It has Mathioya dam on MathioyaRiver and Maragua dam on MaraguaRiver. The source for the two rivers is the Aberdare forest.The station has a total capacity of 7.4MW. Units 1 &amp; 2 are each rated at 2.7MW and they get their water from Mathioya River through a tunnel that is 5.2km long and runs under Murang&rsquo;a town. The water from these machines flows into MaraguaRiver. Units 3 &amp; 4 are served by MaraguaRiver.A project to modernize and upgrade the units has already been awarded to Voith Hydro, Germany. Site installation works are planned to start in June 2019.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><u>&nbsp;</u></p>\r\n<p><u>Units 1 &amp; 2 (Merilla units)</u></p>\r\n<p>Year of commissioning: 1952</p>\r\n<p>Installed capacity: 2 x 2.7MW</p>\r\n<p>Turbine type: Horizontal Francis</p>\r\n<p>Turbine manufacturer:Harland, UK</p>\r\n<p>Design head: &nbsp;{51.2m &ndash; 1 Machine; 40.5m &ndash; 2 Machines}</p>\r\n<p>Design speed: 333rpm</p>\r\n<p>Runner type: Vertical Francis runner</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Generator manufacturer: UCM Hydro Romania</p>\r\n<p>Generator rating: 9100kVA</p>\r\n<p>Generator voltage: 11000V</p>\r\n<p>Generator current: 478A</p>\r\n<p>Rated power: 7735kW</p>\r\n<p>Frequency: 50Hz</p>\r\n<p>Power factor: 0.85</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Excitation voltage: 130V</p>\r\n<p>Excitation current: 520A</p>\r\n<p>Excitation system: Brushes</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><u>Units 03 and 04 (Maragwaunits)</u></p>\r\n<p>Year of commissioning: 1954 units</p>\r\n<p>Installed capacity: 2 x 1.0MW</p>\r\n<p>Turbine type: Horizontal Francis</p>\r\n<p>Turbine manufacture: Harland, UK</p>\r\n<p>Design head: 68.2m</p>\r\n<p>Design speed: 500rpm</p>\r\n<p>Runner type: Vertical Francis runner</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Generator manufacturer: UCM Hydro Romania</p>\r\n<p>Rating: 6070kVA</p>\r\n<p>Rated voltage: 11000V</p>\r\n<p>Rated power: 5159kW</p>\r\n<p>Frequency: 50Hz</p>\r\n<p>Power factor: 0.85</p>\r\n<p><strong><u>&nbsp;</u></strong></p>\r\n<p>Exciter Voltage: 85V</p>\r\n<p>Exciter current: 550A</p>\r\n<p>Excitation System: Brushes</p>\r\n<p>Protection degrees: IP44</p>','','',0,0,1,365,4,'','https://www.google.com/maps/embed?pb=!1m18!1m12!1m3!1d15957.908166356605!2d37.16608821607638!3d-0.7494088062565962!2m3!1f0!2f0!3f0!3m2!1i1024!2i768!4f13.1!3m3!1m2!1s0x0%3A0x4d09769f4794c52d!2sKenGen%20PLC%20Wanjii%20Power%20Station!5e0!3m2!1sen!2ske!4v1581580037518!5m2!1sen!2ske','Address:P. O. BOX 45, 10200,Murang\'a\r\nTel: 0711036000\r\nContact Person:Regional Manager,Eastern','0',8,1,'2019-09-23 10:00:00'),(6,5,'Tana Hydro Power Station ','<p>Tana power station is situated in Murang&rsquo;aCounty &nbsp;82km from Nairobi.The old power plant was retired in 2010. Details for the old plant were as follows;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Two units each 2MW installed in 1933</li>\r\n<li>One unit 2.4MW installed in 1953</li>\r\n<li>Two units each 4.0MW installed in 1955</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>The new power plant was commissioned in 2011.</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Installed Capacity: 2 x 5.5MW&amp;</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>2 x 4.5MW</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Year of Commissioning: 2011</li>\r\n<li>Turbine type: Vertical Francis</li>\r\n<li>Manufacturer: UCM Resita, Romania</li>\r\n<li>Contractor:Farab Energy &amp; Water Projects Ltd, Iran</li>\r\n<li>Engineer:Fichtner, Germany</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>The Tana Power Station lies just upstream of the confluence of the Sagana and MaraguaRivers to form River Tana. The bigger units draw water from Sagana River while the smaller units use water from MaraguaRiver.This is a run-of-river plant with small sized dams having low water storage capacity:Merila dam on SaganaRiver and Maragua dam on MaraguaRiver.</p>','','',0,0,1,365,4,'','https://www.google.com/maps/embed?pb=!1m18!1m12!1m3!1d3989.4433825027363!2d37.2631795140989!3d-0.7854962355048493!2m3!1f0!2f0!3f0!3m2!1i1024!2i768!4f13.1!3m3!1m2!1s0x1828a731ff223151%3A0x5357a2b395f847ce!2sTana%20Hydroelectric%20Power%20Station!5e0!3m2!1sen!2ske!4v1581579216883!5m2!1sen!2ske',NULL,'0',9,1,'2019-09-23 10:00:00'),(7,5,'Sagana Hydro Power Station ','<p>Sagana power station is situated in NyeriCounty &nbsp;betweenKaratina and Nyeri towns 140km from Nairobi.</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Installed capacity: 3 x 0.5MW</li>\r\n<li>Year of commissioning: 1956</li>\r\n<li>Turbine type: Horizontal Francis</li>\r\n<li>Manufacturer: Gilbert Gilkes, UK</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>This is a run-of-river plant with a small sized dam having low water storage capacity. The plant is on Sagana River that has tributaries starting from Mt. Kenya and the Aberdare forests.</p>','','',0,0,1,365,4,'','https://www.google.com/maps/embed?pb=!1m18!1m12!1m3!1d3989.6809215659623!2d37.05024041409743!3d-0.4755035354115836!2m3!1f0!2f0!3f0!3m2!1i1024!2i768!4f13.1!3m3!1m2!1s0x1828620f3ea65d69%3A0xc4a42285673b914!2sKenGen%20Sagana%20Falls!5e0!3m2!1sen!2ske!4v1581578888586!5m2!1sen!2ske',NULL,'0',7,1,'2019-09-23 10:00:00'),(8,2,'Turkwel Hydro Power Station ','<p>Installed capacity: 2x 53MW</p>\r\n<p>Year of installation: 1991</p>\r\n<p>Turbine type: Vertical Francis</p>\r\n<p>Turbine Manufacturer:Neyrpic- France</p>\r\n<p>Generator manufacturer:Alshom-Jeumont (France)</p>\r\n<p>Diversion tunnel: 740m long, 12m high</p>\r\n<p>Headrace tunnel &amp; penstock: 5.5km long, 4-7m dia.</p>\r\n<p>Contractor: SpieBatignolles (France)</p>\r\n<p>Engineer: Sogreah (France)</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Turkwel is situated 560km from Nairobi in North-Western Kenya on the border of West Pokot and Turkana counties. It was constructed under Kerio Valley Development Authority from 1986 to 1991 through partnership of the Kenyan and French governments. Turkwel at inception was a multipurpose project comprising hydro-power, agricultural, fisheries and tourism developments. It uses water from Turkwel River which flows from Mount Elgon catchment area (Suam) in the border of Kenya and Uganda. The water storage dam capacity is 1.6 billion cu. metres and covers 6500 hectares. Water is drawn to an underground power station via 5.5km headrace tunnel/ penstock from an arch dam of 150m maximum height and 150m crown width. The power generated is transmitted to Lessos substation via a 220kV transmission line over a distance of 210 km.</p>','','',0,0,1,365,4,'','','','16',14,1,'2019-09-23 10:00:00'),(9,2,'Gogo Hydro Power Station','<p>Installed capacity: 2x1MW</p>\r\n<p>Year of installation: 1957</p>\r\n<p>Turbine type: Vertical Kaplan</p>\r\n<p>Turbine manufacturer: Riva Milano, Italy</p>\r\n<p>Generator manufacturer: Bruce Peebles &amp; Co</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Gogo is situated 350km from Nairobi and 45 km from Migori town in Migori County . It was constructed in 1957 by the Macalder Mining Company to supply power to its gold mines. It is a run-of-river station drawing water from the Kuja River (also known as Gucha in the neighbouringKisii) in a catchment area of 2,980 sq km. Gogo has a head of 19.8m. Power generated at the station is fed into the 33kV network via Gogo- Awendo distribution line. Some of the power generated is tapped at Gogo substation via a spur to Nyatike&ndash;Muhuru area.</p>','<ol>\r\n<li>Do not litter the compound. Segregate waste and put in the designated waste bins. green bins are for biodegradables and red bins are for non-biodegradable waste.</li>\r\n<li>Visitors are advised not to wear high heeled and open shoes.</li>\r\n<li>Do not lean on the guard rails.</li>\r\n<li>Do not run down the stairs.</li>\r\n<li>Do not touch panels, wires, switch buttons or any equipment.</li>\r\n<li>In case of any fire alarm, do not panic. follow the guide&rsquo;s instructions. he will lead you to emergency assembly point.</li>\r\n<li>Smoking is strictly prohibited in the stations except in the designated smoking zones.</li>\r\n<li>Carrying and use of drugs and alcohol is strictly prohibited.</li>\r\n<li>Provide a list of names of members of your team to the guide and sign the provided form after the EHS awareness briefing.</li>\r\n<li>Photography is prohibited. Visitors will not be allowed tio use data storage devices, for example: flash drives or hard drives. Such devices must be deposited with the security guard at the entrance gate.</li>\r\n<li>Unless authorized, do not connect to the KenGen plants\' communication network(Wi-Fi).</li>\r\n</ol>','',0,160,1,365,4,'','https://www.google.com/maps/embed?pb=!1m18!1m12!1m3!1d2042562.8047592025!2d34.959429980514436!3d-0.8488362127908378!2m3!1f0!2f0!3f0!3m2!1i1024!2i768!4f13.1!3m3!1m2!1s0x19d4af74730900dd%3A0x14c498fd41522fd8!2sGogo%20Hydro%20Power%20Station!5e0!3m2!1sen!2ske!4v1581576527081!5m2!1sen!2ske','Address:P. O. BOX 1058. 40400 Suna Migori\r\nTel: 0711036000\r\nContact Person:Regional Manager,Western','15',15,1,'2019-09-23 10:00:00'),(12,2,'Sang\'oro Hydro Power Station','<p>Installed capacity: 2 x10.6MW</p>\r\n<p>Year of commissioning: 2012</p>\r\n<p>Engineer: Nippon Koei (Japan)</p>\r\n<p>Turbine type: Vertical Francis</p>\r\n<p>Generator manufacturer: Fujian Nandian (China)</p>\r\n<p>Contractor: Sino Hydro (China)</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Sang&rsquo;oro is a cascade power station 4.7km from the Sondu Miriu power station. Water is conveyed from Sondu Miriu tailrace through a 4.7 km channel and a 133.6m length penstock from the head tank to the power station. Water from the station is released through a tailrace back to Sondu Miriu River. Power from the station is fed to the national grid through a 5km long 132kV transmission line to the Sondu Miriu sub-station.</p>','','',0,0,1,365,4,'','','','17',12,1,'2019-09-23 10:00:00'),(13,3,'Kipevu Thermal Power Station','<p><strong>Kipevu 1 Diesel Plant</strong></p>\r\n<p>Installed capacity: 6 x 12.5 MW</p>\r\n<p>Year of commissioning: 1999</p>\r\n<p>Engine manufacturer: MAN DIESEL</p>\r\n<p>Engine type:MAN DIESEL 9L 58/64</p>\r\n<p>Generator manufacturer: ABB</p>\r\n<p>Generator:11KV, 14.4 MVA Synchronous ABB HSG 1600SS14</p>\r\n<p>Kipevu I Diesel Plant, commissioned in 1999, is a thermal plant which has six four-stroke diesel engines. The engines run on Heavy Fuel Oil (HFO) at loads above 6.5MW and Industrial Diesel Oil (IDO) for start up to 6.5MW. The diesel engines are medium speed engines which drive synchronous generators at a synchronous speed of 428 revs/min. The diesel generators generate power at 11kV which is stepped up by power transformers to 132kV into the national grid. Two diesel generators generate into one 30MVA power transformer which means the power station has three power transformers connected to the national grid.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>Kipevu III Diesel Plant</strong></p>\r\n<p>Installed capacity: 7 x 17 MW</p>\r\n<p>Year of commissioning:2011</p>\r\n<p>Engine manufacturer: Wartsila</p>\r\n<p>Engine type: Wartsila W18V46</p>\r\n<p>Generator manufacturer: ABB</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Kipevu III Diesel Plant, commissioned in 2011, is a thermal plant which has seven V-type four-stroke diesel engines. The engines run on Heavy Fuel Oil (HFO) from start up to full load. The diesel engines are medium speed engine which drive synchronous generators at a synchronous speed of 500 revs/min. The diesel generators generate power at 11kV which is stepped up by power transformers to 132kV into the national grid. The station has three power transformers and a Gas Insulated Substation (GIS) for 132kV switchgear.</p>','','',0,160,1,365,4,'','https://www.google.com/maps/embed?pb=!1m18!1m12!1m3!1d3979.9484207564547!2d39.630472014118354!3d-4.030946245912842!2m3!1f0!2f0!3f0!3m2!1i1024!2i768!4f13.1!3m3!1m2!1s0x18406d5fbe4f58cd%3A0xf3fec5f0fe66f34f!2sKipevu%20Power%20Station!5e0!3m2!1sen!2ske!4v1581577233932!5m2!1sen!2ske','','18',17,1,'2019-09-23 10:00:00'),(14,6,'Ngong\' Wind Power Station ','<p><strong>Ngong 1 phase I </strong></p>\r\n<p>Installed capacity: 6 x850kW</p>\r\n<p>Year of commissioning: 2009</p>\r\n<p>Engineer: Vestas, Netherlands</p>\r\n<p>Turbine type: Vestas V52-850kW</p>\r\n<p>Turbine manufacturer: Vestas</p>\r\n<p>Generator manufacturer:ABB</p>\r\n<p>Contractor:TPF Econola (Main), Malta Forest (Civil)</p>\r\n<p>Hub height: 49m</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>Ngong 1 phase II </strong></p>\r\n<p>Installed capacity: 8 x850kW</p>\r\n<p>Year of commissioning: 2013</p>\r\n<p>Engineer: Vestas, Netherlands</p>\r\n<p>Turbine type: Vestas V52-850kW</p>\r\n<p>Turbine manufacturer: Vestas</p>\r\n<p>Generator manufacturer: ABB</p>\r\n<p>Contractor:TPF Econola (Main), Malta Forest (Civil)</p>\r\n<p>Hub height: 49m</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>Ngong phase II </strong></p>\r\n<p>Installed capacity: 16 x 850kW</p>\r\n<p>Year of commissioning:2013</p>\r\n<p>Engineer: Siemens-Gamesa, Spain</p>\r\n<p>Turbine type:Gamesa AG-850kW</p>\r\n<p>Turbine manufacturer: Gamesa</p>\r\n<p>Generator manufacturer: Gamesa</p>\r\n<p>Contractor:Iberdrolla-Gamesa consortium</p>\r\n<p>Hub height:55m</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Ngong Wind farm, located in Kajiado County on the northern part of Ngong Hills, consists of thirty wind turbines having a total installed capacity of 25.5MW. The wind turbines generate power at 690V which is stepped up 11kV to the substation and furtherstepped up by power transformers to 66kV into the national grid. The station has three power transformers.</p>','','',0,0,1,365,4,'','https://www.google.com/maps/embed?pb=!1m18!1m12!1m3!1d3988.6611365393846!2d36.632505914101564!3d-1.3799798361231823!2m3!1f0!2f0!3f0!3m2!1i1024!2i768!4f13.1!3m3!1m2!1s0x182f025e8e495767%3A0x80d00d9c73762c1!2sNgong%20Hills%20Wind%20Power%20Station!5e0!3m2!1sen!2ske!4v1581578602441!5m2!1sen!2ske','','19',16,1,'2019-09-23 10:00:00'),(15,5,'Mesco Hydro Power Station','<p>A new generating machine was installed in in 2013 replacing the old one which was installed in 1930. This increased the rating of the plant to a capacity of 0.43MW up from 0.38MW. The new machine was installed by Gilbert Gilkes, UK who were also the original manufacturer of the 1930 plant.The turbine type is horizontal Francis and draws water from MaraguaRiver. The station is situated in Murang&rsquo;aCounty , just upstream of Wanjii power station. This is a run-of-river plant with a small intake on MaraguaRiver. The source of MaraguaRiver is the Aberdare forest.</p>','','',0,160,1,365,4,'','',NULL,'',10,1,'2019-09-23 10:00:00'),(16,4,'Kindaruma Hydro Power Station','<p><strong>Installed Capacity</strong> &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp; 3 x 24MW</p>\r\n<p><strong>Year of commissioning</strong> &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; Unit 1 &amp; 2: &nbsp;1968 &nbsp;&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; Unit 3: 2013</p>\r\n<p><strong>Turbine manufacturer</strong> &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; BOVING/Andritz</p>\r\n<p><strong>Generator manufacturer</strong> &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; Associated Electric Industries/Andritz</p>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\">Commissioned in 1968, Kindaruma was the first major power station in independent Kenya. It was originally designed with a provision of three turbine generator units, but only two rated at 20MW were installed at the beginning. Subsequent installation of the third 24MW unit and upgrading of the earlier two units from 20MW to 24MW resulting to installed capacity of 72MW.<br /><br />Power from Kindaruma is transmitted directly to Nairobi via a 132KV line or to Kamburu 132KV substation. The water is then passed down to Kiambere Dam. Kindaruma has 3 motorised spillway gates and one trash gate for dam level regulation and removal of trash.</div>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\">&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\"><sup>&nbsp;</sup></div>','<ol>\r\n<li>Do not litter the compound. Segregate waste and put in the designated waste bins. green bins are for biodegradables and red bins are for non-biodegradable waste.</li>\r\n<li>Visitors are advised not to wear high heeled and open shoes.</li>\r\n<li>Do not lean on the guard rails.</li>\r\n<li>Do not run down the stairs.</li>\r\n<li>Do not touch panels, wires, switch buttons or any equipment.</li>\r\n<li>In case of any fire alarm, do not panic. follow the guide&rsquo;s instructions. he will lead you to emergency assembly point.</li>\r\n<li>Smoking is strictly prohibited in the stations except in the designated smoking zones.</li>\r\n<li>Carrying and use of drugs and alcohol is strictly prohibited.</li>\r\n<li>Provide a list of names of members of your team to the guide and sign the provided form after the EHS awareness briefing.</li>\r\n<li>Photography is prohibited. Visitors will not be allowed tio use data storage devices, for example: flash drives or hard drives. Such devices must be deposited with the security guard at the entrance gate.</li>\r\n<li>Unless authorized, do not connect to the KenGen plants\' communication network(Wi-Fi).</li>\r\n</ol>','',0,160,1,365,4,'kindaruma.jpg','https://www.google.com/maps/embed?pb=!1m18!1m12!1m3!1d3989.4196993490737!2d37.810540914098986!3d-0.8099249355188718!2m3!1f0!2f0!3f0!3m2!1i1024!2i768!4f13.1!3m3!1m2!1s0x1826657c201bfe39%3A0x7d9553ab0319d0bc!2sKindaruma%20Power%20Plant!5e0!3m2!1sen!2ske!4v1581577074876!5m2!1sen!2ske','','11',6,1,'2019-09-23 10:00:00'),(17,4,'Gitaru Hydro power station','<p>Installed Capacity &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp; 1 x 80.25 MW &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<br />&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp; 2 x 72.5 MW</p>\r\n<p>Year of commissioning &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;Unit 1: &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; 2000</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; Unit 2 &amp; 3: &nbsp;1977&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Turbine manufacturer &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp; VOITH</p>\r\n<p>Generator manufacturer &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp; SIEMENS</p>\r\n<p>Generator voltage &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp; Unit 1: &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; 15KV</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp; Unit 2 &amp; 3: &nbsp;&nbsp; 11 KV &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>It was the biggest hydro power station in East Africa by the time of commissioning in terms of installed capacity. Two vertical Francis turbines drive generators rated at 85MVA each at a net head of 136m. Water is conveyed to the 3 machines by 5 meter diameter penstocks from the intake. The dam has 3 hydraulic radial spillway gates at the spillway structure used to regulate the dam level during floods. The power produced is transmitted to Kamburu 132kV and 220kV substations, via 132kV and 220kV circuits.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\">The station was upgraded in 1999 with an additional third unit which produces 80MW at 15kV that is stepped up to 220kV and is fed into the national grid at the Kamburu 220kV substation. The water is then passed on to Kindaruma, the oldest power station in the complex via an underground 4.7 kilometer tailrace tunnel.</div>','<ol>\r\n<li>Do not litter the compound. Segregate waste and put in the designated waste bins. green bins are for biodegradables and red bins are for non-biodegradable waste.</li>\r\n<li>Visitors are advised not to wear high heeled and open shoes.</li>\r\n<li>Do not lean on the guard rails.</li>\r\n<li>Do not run down the stairs.</li>\r\n<li>Do not touch panels, wires, switch buttons or any equipment.</li>\r\n<li>In case of any fire alarm, do not panic. follow the guide&rsquo;s instructions. he will lead you to emergency assembly point.</li>\r\n<li>Smoking is strictly prohibited in the stations except in the designated smoking zones.</li>\r\n<li>Carrying and use of drugs and alcohol is strictly prohibited.</li>\r\n<li>Provide a list of names of members of your team to the guide and sign the provided form after the EHS awareness briefing.</li>\r\n<li>Photography is prohibited. Visitors will not be allowed tio use data storage devices, for example: flash drives or hard drives. Such devices must be deposited with the security guard at the entrance gate.</li>\r\n<li>Unless authorized, do not connect to the KenGen plants\' communication network(Wi-Fi).</li>\r\n</ol>','',20,160,1,365,4,'gitaru.png','https://www.google.com/maps/embed?pb=!1m18!1m12!1m3!1d3989.4350467074605!2d37.75013331409882!3d-0.7941801355097208!2m3!1f0!2f0!3f0!3m2!1i1024!2i768!4f13.1!3m3!1m2!1s0x18266ee910a1050b%3A0x273f13e96693c98c!2sGitaru%20Hydroelectrical%20Power%20Plant!5e0!3m2!1sen!2ske!4v1581576181461!5m2!1sen!2ske','<p>P. O. BOX 205, 60100, Embu</p>\r\n<p>Tel: 0711036351/0711035810</p>','9',4,1,'2019-09-23 10:00:00'),(19,2,'Sondu Hydro Power Station','<p>Installed capacity: 2x 30MW</p>\r\n<p>Year of commissioning: 2007</p>\r\n<p>Turbine type: Vertical Francis</p>\r\n<p>Turbine manufacturer: Toshiba</p>\r\n<p>Generator manufacturer: Toshiba</p>\r\n<p>Sondu Miriu Power Station is situated in Kisumu County , 60km from Kisumu town and 350km from Nairobi. It draws water from the Sondu Miriu River whose main catchment area is Mau Forest. Sondu is a run-of-river scheme with an intake weir and holding pond that discharges the required water with a net head of 178m via a 6.2 km tunnel and a 1.2 km penstock to the vertical Francis turbines. Water from the turbines is discharged into an open outlet channel 4.7km long to the 21.2MW Sang&rsquo;oro plant. Power generated is fed into the national grid through a 50km long 132kV transmission line into Mamboleo sub-station in Kisumu. There is a provision for an irrigation intake facility of about 2,380Ha of land in the Kano plains.</p>','','',0,0,1,365,4,'','https://www.google.com/maps/embed?pb=!1m18!1m12!1m3!1d3989.74673141404!2d34.84952336409699!3d-0.343229535419599!2m3!1f0!2f0!3f0!3m2!1i1024!2i768!4f13.1!3m3!1m2!1s0x182ac285f38056e9%3A0x72bd411341a5d89d!2sSondu%20Miriu%20Hydroelectric%20Power%20Station!5e0!3m2!1sen!2ske!4v1581579130723!5m2!1sen!2ske','','13',13,1,'2019-09-23 17:37:17'),(29,2,'Muhoroni Thermal Power Station','<p>Installed capacity: 56MW</p>\r\n<p>Year of installation: 1987 GT1 and 1999 GT2.</p>\r\n<p>Turbine type: 3-Stage Turbo Gas Turbine</p>\r\n<p>Gas turbine model: GE Frame MS6001B</p>\r\n<p>Gas turbine manufacturer: General Electric Company</p>\r\n<p>Generator manufacturer: Brush Electrical Machines</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>The Gas Turbine is a heavy duty three (3) stage Turbo Turbine Model MS6001B running at 5100rpm full speed was manufactured by General Electric Company and is coupled to a 39200kVA synchronous Brush Electrical Generator operating at 3000rpm speed through a reduction Load Gear Box (5100/3000 ratio). The GT is kerosene fired and in turn gives out electrical energy, exhaust gases and other forms of waste energy. The GT1 and GT2 were commissioned in 1986 and 1999 respectively at Kipevu. They operated there until 2010 when they were relocated and commissioned at Embakasi substation in Nairobi County.They were later decommissioned and relocated to Muhoroni in KerichoCounty and commissioned in 2016 for GT1 and 2019 for GT2 to meet the increasing demand of electricity in the Western Region of the country. The gas turbines are the only KenGen generators contracted to supply both active and reactive power to the grid.</p>','','',0,0,1,365,4,'','','','14',11,1,'2019-09-23 17:46:54');
